    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1941-04-29T14:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1941-04-29T14:00:00-05:00" n="521"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d521">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">890G.00/590: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister Resident in Iraq</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Knabenshue</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Baghdad</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1941-04-29T22:00:00+03:00"
                            >April 29, 1941—10 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received April 30—7:30 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>108. British Ambassador informed me this afternoon that he gathers from his long
                    conversation with Gailani yesterday that the Iraq Government may rupture
                    diplomatic relations with Britain on grounds of violation of treaty.</p>
                <p>With established air bases in Iraq and presence of troops which are to be further
                    reinforced middle May the result of such action by Iraq Government would be
                    obvious—crushing of present government and army by the British and restoration
                    of legal Iraqi Government and return of Abdul Allah [<hi rend="italic"
                    >Ilah</hi>] to resume regency. In view of illegality of present government and
                    its hostile attitude interfering with <pb facs="0512" n="504" xml:id="pg_504"/>
                    British war effort it would seem British would be justified in such action.
                    Moreover, most better Iraqi politicians and public would welcome it. Total
                    evacuation of British women and children has alarmed Iraqis. It shows British
                    mean business and it might have salutary effect.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Knabenshue</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
